---
import Layout from '@/layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '@/components/Header.astro';

const title = 'Why the AEGIS Policy DSL refuses to relax defaults';
const date = '2026-05-18';
const description =
  'The single design decision that decides whether your agent-security product survives a SOC 2 audit.';
---

<Layout title={`${title} — Aojie Yuan`} description={description}>
  <main>
    <Header current="writing" />

    <article>
      <header class="post-head">
        <a href="/writing" class="back">← Writing</a>
        <time datetime={date}>
          {new Date(date).toLocaleDateString('en-US', { year: 'numeric', month: 'long', day: 'numeric' })}
        </time>
        <h1>{title}</h1>
        <p class="lede">{description}</p>
      </header>

      <section class="prose">
        <p>
          When I started designing the per-tenant Policy DSL for AEGIS, the
          obvious question was: should a tenant's DSL be able to override the
          default rules? In other words — if my AJV-based <code>sql-injection</code>
          policy says <em>block</em>, but the tenant's DSL says <em>allow</em>,
          who wins?
        </p>
        <p>
          The "flexible" answer is "the tenant wins, that's what
          <em>customization</em> means." The "industrial-grade" answer turns
          out to be the opposite: the strictest verdict always wins, and the
          tenant's DSL can only ever <em>tighten</em>.
        </p>

        <h2>Three reasons the strict reading is right</h2>

        <p>
          <strong>SOC 2 / pen-test posture.</strong> An auditor's first
          question on a security product is "show me the config that prevents
          allow from overriding block." If your answer is "trust the
          customer," the report gets a finding. If your answer is "the system
          is <em>structurally</em> incapable of relaxing defaults," the
          finding disappears and the conversation moves on.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Liability shape.</strong> When a tenant writes
          <code>{`{rules: [{name: yolo, then: {decision: allow}}]}`}</code> and
          a SQL injection later lands in production, who's responsible? With
          fail-safe semantics, the answer is unambiguously the tenant — they
          had to <em>actively disable</em> the default policy via a separate,
          audited code path. With override semantics, the lawyer's letter
          shows up at <em>your</em> door, not theirs.
        </p>
        <p>
          <strong>Industry consensus.</strong> Lakera Guard, Cisco AI Defense,
          Palo Alto Prisma AIRS, NVIDIA NeMo Guardrails — none of them let a
          downstream user-written rail relax an upstream block. The whole
          guardrail category quietly converged on fail-safe, and any product
          that doesn't will look out of place in a procurement comparison
          matrix.
        </p>

        <h2>What "customization" still means</h2>

        <p>
          You don't actually need allow-override to ship a customization
          story. The DSL can still:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>route specific tool categories to human review per tenant;</li>
          <li>escalate on anomaly score, agent identity, or deployment mode;</li>
          <li>add brand-new block rules the defaults don't cover;</li>
          <li>flip the decision from <em>allow</em> to <em>pending</em> for
          ambiguous calls.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          That covers roughly the same surface as Lakera's per-route policy
          profiles or Lasso's Intent Deputy — without giving the customer a
          loaded gun to put through their own foot.
        </p>

        <h2>What if a customer really, truly insists?</h2>

        <p>
          There's already a path: AEGIS exposes default policies as first-
          class records via the Policy API. A customer who needs to allow
          something that <code>supply-chain</code> blocks can
          <code>DELETE /api/v1/policies/source-map-leak</code>. That's a
          RBAC-gated, audit-logged operation. The boundary is clean — the
          customer takes deliberate ownership of the gap, and we can prove
          every act of relaxation came from an authenticated admin.
        </p>

        <h2>If you're shipping something similar</h2>

        <p>
          You can always add <em>looser</em> semantics later if a customer
          stamps their foot hard enough. Going from fail-safe → opt-in
          override is a couple of config bits. Going from override →
          fail-safe is a breaking change that someone, somewhere, will catch
          in their next pen test.
        </p>
        <p>
          Ship the strict version. Add a flag if you have to.
        </p>
      </section>
    </article>
  </main>

  <style>
    main {
      max-width: 640px;
      margin: 0 auto;
      padding: 1.5rem 1.75rem 6rem;
    }
    .post-head {
      margin: 4rem 0 3rem;
    }
    .back {
      font-size: 0.85rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      border-bottom-color: transparent;
      display: inline-block;
      margin-bottom: 2rem;
    }
    .back:hover {
      color: var(--text);
      border-bottom-color: var(--text);
    }
    .post-head time {
      font-size: 0.78rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      letter-spacing: 0.05em;
      text-transform: uppercase;
      display: block;
      margin-bottom: 0.7rem;
    }
    h1 {
      font-size: clamp(2rem, 5vw, 3rem);
      line-height: 1.15;
      margin: 0 0 1.2rem;
      letter-spacing: -0.014em;
    }
    .lede {
      font-size: 1.1rem;
      color: var(--muted);
      max-width: 46ch;
      line-height: 1.55;
      margin: 0;
    }
    .prose {
      font-size: 1.04rem;
      line-height: 1.72;
    }
    .prose h2 {
      font-size: 1.55rem;
      margin: 3rem 0 1rem;
      line-height: 1.3;
    }
    .prose p {
      margin: 0 0 1.3rem;
    }
    .prose ul {
      padding-left: 1.3rem;
      margin: 0 0 1.5rem;
    }
    .prose li {
      margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    }
    .prose code {
      background: var(--surface);
      padding: 0.1rem 0.4rem;
      border-radius: 3px;
      font-size: 0.86em;
      border: 1px solid var(--hairline);
    }
    .prose em {
      font-style: italic;
      color: var(--accent);
    }
    .prose strong {
      font-weight: 600;
      color: var(--text);
    }
  </style>
</Layout>
